Just something short. More of a set-up than an actual story.


It's Halloween, and Anon's office is having a festive party. Not a Halloween party, but a Christmas party, because within a month the entire office will be liquidated and everyone will be out of a job. The Christmas parties were always a bigger hit than the Halloween ones, and so the higher ups decided it'd be better to go out on a higher note.

It was actually a pretty good party, assuming you didn't know it wasn't even the right month for it. There was a healthy buzz of chatter and ambient music, the rich smells of an actual Christmas roast permeated through most of the office, a few presents sat in a pile near the food platters, and despite the imminent unemployment, most people seemed to be smiling and laughing freely.

Anon didn't have many friends in the office. He kept to himself mostly, did his work and went home. He was friendly enough with his co-workers, but an awkward nod in the break room and a casual 'Did you see the game last night?' didn't make much of a friendship. And so he walked through the office, already on his third mug of eggnog, wondering why he even came to the party.

One of Anon's office managers, Miss Harper, a reindeer well into her early forties, was standing by the present pile, listing everyone who had brought in a present. She always appeared quiet and sombre, and today was no exception. Occasionally one of the drunker employees would make a comment about her pulling their sleigh, or offering her a kiss under the mistletoe. Like always, she simply sighed and stared them down until they went away. She hated Christmas parties. She hated Christmas. Everyone always jumped to the annoying stereotype that reindeer must love everything about Christmas time. She'd worked there for nearly a decade, and every year it was the same thing. What made it worse was that it wasn't even Christmas yet. A part of her was glad that the place was getting shut down.

Harper sighed again as another worker approached her, no present in sight but a half-empty mug in hand. She waited for him to make some hackneyed joke at her expense, clicking the end of her pen while she waited. He barely came up to her shoulders, though that was probably the right size for a human. Maybe a little taller than the other ones she'd seen. She didn't remember his name, but she did recognise him. Started here a couple years ago, fresh out of school no doubt. Probably his first real job. He did good enough work, kept his nose clean and didn't break anything. More than could be said of his coworkers.

Anon swallowed his nerves, and the last of the eggnog coating the insides of his cheeks, looking up at the stern glare of his reindeer manager. She posed a fairly intimidating figure, tall and thickset, a cleanly pressed blouse hugging her figure closely and a firm scowl lining her face. They hadn't spoken much, outside doing his job, but she had always seemed polite, and she sometimes complimented him on his work. He also thought she was especially pretty, but it would have been completely unprofessional to say anything like that to her, and even if it wasn't, he didn't think anything could come of it except awkwardness. He found himself standing silently in front of Harper while she stared and clicked her pen every so often.

"I think you're incredibly beautiful, Miss Harper, I wish this place wasn't getting shut down so I could see you more." The reindeer slowly blinked at Anon, and he took another sip from his mug. His cheeks turned crimson red as he slowly realised he had actually said those words, instead of just thinking them. He gulped down the last of his eggnog, trying to drown the sudden tightness in his chest with the warm buzz of alcohol. "Uh, merry... Halloween?"

Harper watched as the human stammered and turned, then almost began sprinting to the buffet table, filling his mug to the brim with more eggnog. What a strange creature.
